<div class="theory-wrap"><div class="theory">
  <div class="theory-hdr">Theory — What Is Happening Here?</div>

  <h3>The Double-Slit Experiment</h3>
  <p>First performed by Thomas Young with light in 1801, this experiment became one of the most celebrated in physics when it was repeated with single electrons. A stream of quantum particles — photons, electrons, even entire molecules — is fired at a barrier with two narrow slits. Instead of forming two bands on the detector (as classical bullets would), the particles produce an <em>interference pattern</em> of alternating bright and dark fringes.</p>

  <h3>Constructive and Destructive Interference</h3>
  <p>Each slit acts as a new wave source. Where the wavefronts from both slits arrive <em>in phase</em> (crest meets crest), they reinforce — a bright fringe. Where they arrive <em>out of phase</em> (crest meets trough), they cancel — a dark fringe.</p>
  <div class="eq">d · sin θ = m · λ &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(bright fringe at angle θ)
    <div class="vars">d = slit separation · θ = angle from the central axis · λ = wavelength · m = 0, ±1, ±2 ... (fringe order)<br>m=0 → central bright spot · m=±1 → first fringes on either side · and so on</div>
  </div>
  <div class="eq">Δy = λ · L / d &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;(fringe spacing on screen)
    <div class="vars">L = distance from slits to screen · Larger d → fringes closer together · Larger λ → fringes spread further apart</div>
  </div>
  <p>The full intensity pattern also includes a single-slit diffraction envelope from each slit's finite width <em>a</em>, which modulates the fringe heights — fringes near the edge of the envelope are dimmer than the central ones.</p>
  <div class="eq">I(θ) ∝ cos²(πd sinθ/λ) × [sin(πa sinθ/λ) / (πa sinθ/λ)]²
    <div class="vars">First term: double-slit interference · Second term (sinc²): single-slit diffraction envelope<br>Together they predict the exact brightness of each fringe</div>
  </div>

  <h3>The Quantum Mystery: One Particle at a Time</h3>
  <div class="qbox">
    <strong>Key experiment (Tonomura et al., 1989):</strong> Single electrons were fired one at a time through a double slit — so slowly that no two electrons were ever in the apparatus simultaneously. Each electron hit a single pinpoint on the detector. Yet after accumulating ~70,000 electrons, the interference pattern emerged perfectly. Each particle appears to travel through <em>both slits at once</em> as a probability wave, interfering with itself, then collapsing to a point upon detection.
  </div>
  <p>In this simulation, <strong>Quantum mode</strong> fires particles whose landing positions are sampled from the quantum probability distribution |ψ|² = I(θ). Each particle hits one random spot — you cannot predict which — but over many particles the interference pattern is revealed. This is the central mystery of quantum mechanics.</p>

  <h3>Classical Mode: The "Which-Path" Detector</h3>
  <p>Switch to <strong>Classical mode</strong>. Now the pattern becomes two blobs with no fringes. This represents what happens when a detector is placed at the slits to observe which slit the particle passes through — so-called "which-path information." The moment you know which slit was used, the quantum superposition collapses. The interference disappears. The act of observation physically alters the outcome. This is not a flaw in our instruments; it is a fundamental law of nature described by the uncertainty principle.</p>

  <h3>The de Broglie Wavelength</h3>
  <p>Louis de Broglie (1924) proposed that all matter has an associated wavelength. This explains why the experiment works for particles, not just light.</p>
  <div class="eq">λ = h / p = h / √(2mE)
    <div class="vars">h = 6.626 × 10⁻³⁴ J·s (Planck's constant) · p = momentum · m = particle mass · E = kinetic energy<br>For electrons: λ (nm) ≈ 1.226 / √V where V = accelerating voltage in volts<br>For photons: E = hc/λ, so λ (nm) = 1240 / E (eV)</div>
  </div>
  <p>This wavelength must be comparable to the slit size d for interference to be visible. A baseball has λ ≈ 10⁻³⁴ m — far smaller than any physical slit, which is why we never see baseballs interfere with themselves. Electrons and photons at nanometre scales do.</p>

  <table class="utab">
    <tr><td>h (Planck's constant)</td><td>= 6.626 × 10⁻³⁴ J·s</td></tr>
    <tr><td>mₑ (electron mass)</td><td>= 9.109 × 10⁻³¹ kg</td></tr>
    <tr><td>c (speed of light)</td><td>= 2.998 × 10⁸ m/s</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1 eV</td><td>= 1.602 × 10⁻¹⁹ J</td></tr>
    <tr><td>1 nm</td><td>= 10⁻⁹ m = 10 Å (ångström)</td></tr>
    <tr><td>Simulation scale</td><td>1 pixel = 1 nm</td></tr>
  </table>
</div></div>

